<!-- Hero --------------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="hero">
  <div class="inner">
    <span class="eyebrow">Section 04 · Finance</span>
    <h1 class="display">
      Two <span class="accent">revenue streams</span>. One <span class="accent">subscription</span>.
    </h1>
    <p class="lead">
      The live site names three plans — Core, Growth, Performance — but doesn't price them. The sprint built the model that does: a fixed subscription fee (where our margin lives) plus a monthly credit pool the client spends on services from the ALC Menu (where our delivery partners earn 75% of cost). Different economics, different logic, one monthly invoice.
    </p>
  </div>
  <img class="hero-arrow" src="assets/brand-assets/arrow-charcoal.png" alt="">
</section>

<!-- Starting point vs current landing ---------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: var(--s-8);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">The shift</span>
      <h2>From plan names → to a two-stream revenue model.</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        gritfuel.works lists Core / Growth / Performance as plans and deliberately doesn't quote a number — pricing happens in the sales conversation. That's fine for the first handful of clients. It breaks the moment we run more than one cohort in parallel. The sprint closes that gap with a model that separates our subscription economics from our delivery economics, explicitly.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="themes" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;">
      <div class="theme-card t-strategy" style="min-height: auto;">
        <div class="accent-bar"></div>
        <span class="num">STARTING POINT · gritfuel.works</span>
        <span class="title" style="font-size: 22px;">Three plans, no numbers</span>
        <p class="desc">
          Core, Growth, Performance. Scope described in narrative terms. Price discovered case-by-case in a sales call. Fine for bespoke engagements; doesn't scale past ~5 active clients without margin drift.
        </p>
        <p class="desc small" style="color: var(--gray);">Case-by-case · Negotiated · Hard to forecast</p>
      </div>

      <div class="theme-card t-finance" style="min-height: auto;">
        <div class="accent-bar"></div>
        <span class="num">CURRENT LANDING · this sprint</span>
        <span class="title" style="font-size: 22px;">Fixed + credit · two streams</span>
        <p class="desc">
          Every plan splits into a <strong>fixed fee</strong> (high margin, covers GritFuel OS access + ops) and a <strong>credit pool</strong> (variable, 75% flows to delivery partners as service cost). Clients spend credits via the ALC Menu.
        </p>
        <p class="desc small" style="color: var(--gray);">Systematic · Defensible · Forecastable</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Two streams — the big idea ---------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: 0;">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">The model, on one page</span>
      <h2>Stream 1: the subscription. Stream 2: the credit pool.</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        The headline number the client sees is one monthly invoice. Inside that invoice, two different economies run side-by-side. Both are real revenue. Each has its own cost logic, margin profile, and partner destination.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="themes" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; margin-top: var(--s-6);">
      <!-- Stream 1 -->
      <div class="theme-card t-finance" style="min-height: auto;">
        <div class="accent-bar"></div>
        <span class="num">STREAM 1 · FIXED SUBSCRIPTION FEE</span>
        <span class="title" style="font-size: 22px;">Access to the OS</span>
        <p class="desc">
          <strong>What the client pays for:</strong> access to GritFuel OS (Compounding Engine, Dashboard, Escalation Router, Intake, Credit Allocation, Monthly Playbook), the operator time behind the rhythm, the ops overhead that makes the monthly cycle land on time.
        </p>
        <p class="desc">
          <strong>Per tier / month:</strong><br>
          Core <strong>€1,750</strong> · Growth <strong>€2,500</strong> · Performance <strong>€3,500</strong>
        </p>
        <p class="desc">
          <strong>Margin profile:</strong> high. This is where the economics of the business live. Predictable MRR. Scales linearly with cohort count until we hit the capacity ceiling.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Stream 2 -->
      <div class="theme-card t-product" style="min-height: auto;">
        <div class="accent-bar"></div>
        <span class="num">STREAM 2 · CREDIT POOL SPEND</span>
        <span class="title" style="font-size: 22px;">Services from the ALC Menu</span>
        <p class="desc">
          <strong>What the client pays for:</strong> services — creative, paid media, performance, analytics, content, SEO, PR, social, email, events — drawn from the ALC Menu. <strong>1 credit = €25 output value.</strong> Priced at ~70% of EU benchmarks.
        </p>
        <p class="desc">
          <strong>Per tier / month:</strong><br>
          Core <strong>€1,750</strong> (70 credits) · Growth <strong>€2,750</strong> (110 credits) · Performance <strong>€4,500</strong> (180 credits)
        </p>
        <p class="desc">
          <strong>Margin profile:</strong> thin by design. <strong>75% of credit-pool cost flows to the delivery partners</strong> (.frank, Bluegyfu, BFL — all common ownership with GritFuel). 25% is our margin on services. Paid media runs at cost.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout" style="margin-top: var(--s-6);">
      <h4>Why this framing matters</h4>
      <p style="margin:0;">
        Calling it "plan + add-ons" collapses these two economies into something that reads like an agency retainer. It isn't. Stream 1 is subscription economics (SaaS-like margin on access). Stream 2 is a productised services marketplace (marketplace margin, partner cost share). The capital efficiency of the whole thing rests on keeping these separate in our heads, our quotes, and our books.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout lime" style="margin-top: var(--s-5);">
      <h4>Headline the client sees</h4>
      <p style="margin:0;">
        <strong>Core €3,500/mo · Growth €5,250/mo · Performance €8,000/mo.</strong> One price, one invoice, one monthly rhythm. The two-stream structure lives in the back-office. 3-month credit rollover.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- How the pieces fit ------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: 0;">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">How the artefacts connect</span>
      <h2>Cost → Capacity → Quote → Services catalog.</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        The Fixed-Cost Model sizes what Stream 1 must earn to sustain the business. The Headcount &amp; Capacity Plan sets how many clients we can actually run at that margin. The Scoping Configurator turns an intake brief into a plan tier + a quote. The ALC Menu is the services catalog a client spends their credit pool on — it's <em>where</em> the Stream 2 economy happens, not a list of upsells.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Key decisions -->
    <div class="section-head" style="margin-top: var(--s-8);">
      <span class="eyebrow">Key decisions</span>
      <h2>What's locked, what's open.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="decisions">
      <div class="decision locked">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Two-stream revenue model — locked</h4>
          <p>Fixed subscription fee (Stream 1) + credit pool (Stream 2) is the model. 75% cost-share on Stream 2 flowing to delivery partners is the deal. This is the foundation — everything else sits on it.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Locked</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision locked">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Core / Growth / Performance plan names — locked</h4>
          <p>Carried forward from the live site. Keeps continuity with anything founders have already seen. We change the mechanics inside, not the labels.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Locked</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision locked">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>ALC Menu is the services catalog for the credit pool</h4>
          <p>Not an add-on menu, not edge cases — it <em>is</em> Stream 2's product surface. Every credit a client spends resolves to an ALC line item with a partner destination and a margin impact.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Locked</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Do plan prices appear on the public site?</h4>
          <p>The live site deliberately doesn't price. v2 gives us the option to publish the headline (Core €3,500 / Growth €5,250 / Performance €8,000). Pro: qualifies leads. Con: anchors the negotiation lower than a sales call would.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Do we expose the two-stream split to clients, or just the headline?</h4>
          <p>Showing the split makes our margin on Stream 1 transparent and the partner cost share on Stream 2 visible. Clean, defensible — but also negotiable. Showing only the headline keeps it simple and preserves pricing power.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Performance tier — how much is outcome-based?</h4>
          <p>Options: (a) Stream 1 stays fixed, performance is a bonus on Stream 2 outcomes; (b) lower Stream 1 fee + rev share on client growth; (c) pure rev share. All three are supported by the model — the question is risk appetite.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Extra credits mid-month — allowed, capped, or upgrade-only?</h4>
          <p>Question: what happens when a client burns through their pool before the cycle resets? Options: (a) no top-ups — wait or upgrade; (b) unlimited top-ups at standard €25/credit — simple but uncapped capacity exposure; (c) capped top-ups at flat rate — protects delivery capacity, forces upgrade conversations beyond the cap.</p>
          <p>Proposal: option (c). Allow top-ups up to <strong>25% of the plan's pool size per month</strong> at the standard €25/credit (no premium). Beyond that, the Escalation Router surfaces a plan-tier upgrade conversation instead of letting credits sprawl. No premium pricing on top-ups — we want clients asking for more work <em>inside</em> the OS, not penalising them for it. The discipline comes from the cap, not the price. Open question: is 25% the right ceiling, or do we want a tighter hard cap (e.g. +20 credits regardless of tier) so Performance clients can't quietly absorb +45 credits a month without a capacity conversation?</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>€750 "Compound Diagnosis" — paid entry-point below Core?</h4>
          <p>Question: do we offer a paid, short-form diagnostic engagement that sits below the Core subscription, as a way to qualify-and-convert without discounting the subscription itself?</p>
          <p>Proposal: a <strong>two-week, €750 fixed-fee "Compound Diagnosis"</strong> before any plan commitment. Scope: one Onboarding Intake session + a Compounding Engine baseline pass (their Compound Score + top three momentum leaks) + a 60-minute read-out. Output: a 4–6 page diagnosis doc naming their score, biggest leaks, and recommended plan tier. <strong>Credit-back mechanic:</strong> if they sign a full plan within 30 days, the €750 is credited back as month-one credits (or waived) — removes the "I already paid" friction without cheapening the subscription. Why it works: solves a real objection ("how do I know this fits me before committing €3,500/mo?"), makes outbound <em>far</em> easier (€750 ask vs. €3,500/mo ask), and generates high-signal qualification. Ideal cohort-one mechanic. Watchout: don't let it drift into a standalone consulting product — the credit-back is what prevents that.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Capacity plan — which post-cohort-one hire goes first?</h4>
          <p>The capacity plan supports a phased hire after cohort one clears. Which role comes first: a second operator, a designer, or a data/analytics lead? Each has a different effect on our Stream 1 margin and cohort ceiling.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Artefacts ---------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band dark" style="padding-top: var(--s-8); padding-bottom: var(--s-8);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">The artefacts</span>
      <h2>Open these in order.</h2>
      <p>Fixed-Cost Model first (what Stream 1 must earn). Capacity Plan second (what we can actually run). Scoping Configurator third (how we quote a client). ALC Menu fourth (the Stream 2 catalog). Pricing v7 last (how the tiers present to the client).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="artefacts">

      <!-- Fixed cost -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag xls">XLSX · Stream 1 model</span>
        <h3>Fixed-Cost Model</h3>
        <p class="desc">The Stream 1 baseline. Rent, tooling, partner draws, operator costs, ops overhead — modelled across lean / base / stretch scenarios. Sets the floor every Core / Growth / Performance subscription fee has to clear.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the Scenarios tab — base assumes three operator seats. Challenge that if it feels wrong given cohort-one shape.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn ghost" href="downloads/GritFuel_Fixed_Cost_Model.xlsx" download>Download .xlsx</a>
          <a class="btn ghost" href="downloads/GritFuel_Fixed_Cost_Model_Hybrid.xlsx" download>Hybrid variant .xlsx</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Capacity -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag xls">XLSX · Supply plan</span>
        <h3>Headcount &amp; Capacity Plan</h3>
        <p class="desc">How many clients we can serve in parallel at each plan tier, by month, with and without incremental hires. Determines when a hiring decision becomes load-bearing, and what the Stream 1 margin looks like at each capacity step.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the month-6 row — this is where we hit the first hiring decision and where the margin profile changes.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn ghost" href="downloads/GritFuel_Headcount_Capacity_Plan.xlsx" download>Download .xlsx</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Scoping -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag xls">XLSX · Quote engine</span>
        <h3>Scoping Configurator</h3>
        <p class="desc">A working spreadsheet that takes an intake brief and returns plan tier, credit-pool sizing, and a quote. Used live on sales calls. Drops out to a PDF quote that separates Stream 1 (fixed) and Stream 2 (credit pool) cleanly.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the credit-pool-sizing logic — sanity-check the credit counts per tier against your own reading of a typical month.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn ghost" href="downloads/GritFuel_Scoping_Configurator.xlsx" download>Download .xlsx</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ALC -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag xls">XLSX · Stream 2 catalog</span>
        <h3>ALC Menu v2 — the services catalog</h3>
        <p class="desc">The catalog of services a client buys with their monthly credits. Every line item has: a credit price (1 credit = €25 output value), a delivery partner (.frank / Bluegyfu / BFL / in-house), a turnaround time, and a margin line. This <em>is</em> Stream 2 — not a menu of extras, but the product surface for the credit pool.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the credit-pricing column against your own read of the market. Flag anything that feels over- or under-priced relative to the 70%-of-EU-benchmark anchor.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn ghost" href="downloads/GritFuel_ALC_Menu_v2.xlsx" download>Download .xlsx</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Pricing v7 -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag html">HTML · Client-facing tiers</span>
        <h3>Pricing v7 — how the tiers present</h3>
        <p class="desc">The client-facing view of the three plans — how the two-stream logic translates into a single headline price and a single monthly invoice. Comes with a review companion noting the five issues to fix before go-live.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> whether the headline (€3,500 / €5,250 / €8,000) leads, or whether the fixed-vs-credit split is visible. That's the public-site call.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn" href="artefacts/pricing_v7.html" target="_blank">Open v7 →</a>
          <a class="btn ghost" href="artefacts/pricing_review.html" target="_blank">Review notes →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Asks --------------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: var(--s-8);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="asks">
      <span class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--lime);">What I need from you</span>
      <h3>Three specific questions on Finance.</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Publish prices?</strong> Do the Core / Growth / Performance headline numbers (€3,500 / €5,250 / €8,000) appear on the public site, or stay discovered in conversation?</li>
        <li><strong>Stream transparency:</strong> do we show clients the fixed-vs-credit split (clean, defensible, negotiable) or only the headline (simpler, stronger pricing power)?</li>
        <li><strong>Performance tier:</strong> bonus on Stream 2 outcomes, lower Stream 1 + rev share, or pure rev share? Where's the group's risk appetite?</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

